etymologies: late 19th century. From ancient Greek ἑν-, stem of εἷς (masculine) one + εἴκοσι twenty + -ane, after German Heneicosan

definitions: Any of the hydrocarbons of the alkane series having twenty-one carbon atoms, especially the unbranched isomer (also "n-heneicosane"), a waxy solid which is a component of petroleum and of safflower and some other plant oils.
